 circle of Beat cohorts, but his powerful, startling, innovative work would come to impact American poetry to the present day. Drawing on Whalen’s journals and personal correspondence—particularly with Ginsberg, Kerouac, Snyder, Kyger, Welch, and McClure —David Schneider shows how deeply bonded these intimates were, supporting one another in their art and their spiritual paths. Schneider, himself an ordained priest, provides an insider’s view of Whalen’s struggles and breakthroughs in his thirty years as a Zen monk. When Whalen died in 2002 as the retired Abbot of the Hartford Street Zen Center, his own teacher referred to him as a patriarch of the Western lineage of Buddhism. Crowded by Beauty chronicles the course of Whalen’s life, focusing on his unique, eccentric, humorous, and literary-religious practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBeats (Persons) 0aBeats (Persons). 0aPoets, Americany20th century. 0aZen Buddhists. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / General (see also PHILOSOPHY / Buddhist).2bisacsh  a1950s.  a1960s.  aabbot of hartford street zen center.  aamerican poetry.  aamerican poets.  abeat biography.  abeat generation.  abeat poetry.  aben fagan.  abio.  abiography.  abuddha.  abuddhism.  abuddhist poetry.  acalifornia.  aginsberg.  akeruoac.  anamthar.  anonfiction.  aphilip whalen.  apoetry.  apoets.  areligion.  areligious poetry.  areligious practice.  asan francisco renaissance.  asan francisco.  aspirituality.  astudents and teachers.  averse.  awarren coughlin.  awest coast.  awestern buddhism.  azen buddhists.  azen monk.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052024746840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096099240uhttps://www.degr